<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,358,745]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,392,358,384]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Expanded tentacular membrane. No branchiae. Notochaetae from segment 
<number box="[1277,1292,359,385]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="2.0">2</number>
or 
<number box="[264,279,399,425]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="3.0">3</number>
and 
<number box="[341,442,399,425]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="40.0" valueMax="70.0" valueMin="10.0">10 to 70</number>
segments with notochaetae. Notochaetae pinnate, hirsute or smooth with narrow wings. Thoracic uncini present or absent. Abdominal uncini always present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,358,745]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,451,478,504]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Discussion.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hutchings" box="[463,804,479,505]" pageId="2" pageNumber="7" refString="Hutchings, P. A. &amp; Glasby, C. J. (1986) The Polycirrinae (Polychaeta: Terebellidae) from Australia. Records of Australian Museum, 38, 319 - 350." type="journal article" year="1986">
Hutchings &amp; Glasby (
<number box="[735,796,479,505]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1986.0">1986</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
pointed out that the tentacular membrane expanded anteriorly along the medial axis and laterally to form a trilobated membrane is derived from the prostomium. However, Garraffoni &amp; Lana (submitted) suggested that the tentacular membrane, or upper lip, is a structure localized in the anterior dorsal part of the mouth. Therefore, the ventral continuation of the upper lip was named as the lower lip. Thus, the upper and lower lip considered as a peristomial presegmental region of the body surrounding the mouth (
<bibRefCitation author="Fauchald" box="[546,836,719,745]" pageId="2" pageNumber="7" refString="Fauchald, K. &amp; Rouse, G. W. (1997) Polychaete systematics: Past and present. Zoologica Scripta, 26, 71 - 138." type="journal article" year="1997">
Fauchald &amp; Rouse, 
<number box="[776,836,719,745]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rouse" box="[848,998,719,745]" pageId="2" pageNumber="7" refString="Rouse, G. W. (2000) Polychaetes have evolved feeding larvae numerous times. Bulletin of Marine Science, 67, 391 - 409." type="journal article" year="2000">
Rouse, 
<number box="[936,998,719,745]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Glasby" box="[1010,1168,719,745]" pageId="2" pageNumber="7" refString="Glasby, C. (2001) Glossary of Polychaete Technical Terms and Synonyms. Available from http: // biodiversity. uno. edu / ~ worms / glos-tb. html (accessed 20 Sept. 2003)." type="journal article" year="2001">
Glasby, 
<number box="[1105,1168,719,745]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
